t elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"ce5555c" data-element_type=3D"wi=
dget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default"><p>SRM approaches remain the=
oretical=E2=80=94no one is deploying the technology and there have only bee=
n a few small outdoors experiments. In general the evidence that we have on=
 SRM=E2=80=99s impacts comes from observing&nbsp; the climate effects of vo=
lcanic eruptions, and from computer modelling research, where scientists us=
e climate models to evaluate how SRM might reduce, increase, or alter the i=
mpacts of global warming.</p></div><div class=3D"elementor-element elemento=
r-element-aaeffc1 elementor-widget elementor-widget-heading" data-id=3D"aae=
ffc1" data-element_type=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"heading.default"><h2=
 class=3D"elementor-heading-title elementor-size-default">Why is SRM being =
considered?</h2></div><div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-54c=
4848 elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"54c4848" dat=
a-element_type=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default"><p>SRM i=
s no one=E2=80=99s preferred way to deal with the risks of climate change. =
It would involve directly intervening in the Earth=E2=80=99s climate system=
 and it has some serious risks and large unknowns. But it=E2=80=99s being c=
onsidered because it=E2=80=99s the only known way to quickly slow or revers=
e the rise in global temperatures, and it therefore might prove a useful co=
mplement to controlling greenhouse gases and adapting to the effects of war=
ming.</p></div><div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-86a5db3 el=
ementor-widget elementor-widget-heading" data-id=3D"86a5db3" data-element_t=
ype=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"heading.default"><h3 class=3D"elementor-=
heading-title elementor-size-default">The climate challenge</h3></div><div =
class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-720a8d0 elementor-widget eleme=
ntor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"720a8d0" data-element_type=3D"widget" d=
ata-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default"><p>The world is not on track to mee=
t its international climate change goals and impacts are rising. With curre=
nt climate policies, warming is projected to rise beyond 2.5C and the clima=
te-vulnerable countries of the Global South are going to suffer most.</p></=
div><div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-bd42cfe elementor-wid=
get elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"bd42cfe" data-element_type=3D"=
widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default"><p>Ending greenhouse gas e=
missions is the primary strategy to limit global warming. Adaptation can he=
lp limit risks from increasing warming. Carbon dioxide removal will also pl=
ay an increasing role. However, collectively, these forms of action may not=
 be enough to sufficiently limit risks.</p><p>Scientists are therefore tryi=
ng to understand whether SRM could help reduce the impacts of warming while=
 humanity is eliminating greenhouse gas emissions.&nbsp;</p></div></div></d=
iv></div></section><div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-6874fe=
e elementor-widget elementor-widget-image" data-id=3D"6874fee" data-element=
_type=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"image.default"><figure class=3D"wp-cap=
tion"> <img decoding=3D"async" width=3D"10681" height=3D"6899" src=3D"data:=
image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" =
data-src=3D"https://www.degrees.ngo/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/Napkin-Diagr=
am_v1-w.png" class=3D"attachment-full size-full wp-image-6363 lazyload" alt=
=3D"SRM Napkin Diagram" data-srcset=3D"https://www.degrees.ngo/wp-content/u=
ploads/2022/11/Napkin-Diagram_v1-w.png 10681w, https://www.degrees.ngo/wp-c=
ontent/uploads/2022/11/Napkin-Diagram_v1-w-300x194.png 300w, https://www.de=
grees.ngo/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/Napkin-Diagram_v1-w-1024x661.png 1024w=
, https://www.degrees.ngo/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/Napkin-Diagram_v1-w-76=
8x496.png 768w, https://www.degrees.ngo/wp-content/uploads/2022/11/Napkin-D=
iagram_v1-w-1536x992.png 1536w, https://www.degrees.ngo/wp-content/uploads/=
2022/11/Napkin-Diagram_v1-w-2048x1323.png 2048w"><figcaption class=3D"widge=
t-image-caption wp-caption-text">Napkin diagram roughly showing SRM's role =
in managing climate risks (this work is licensed under a Creative Commons A=
ttribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International License.)</figcaption=
></figure></div><div class=3D"elementor-element elementor-element-dfe4d14 e=
lementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor" data-id=3D"dfe4d14" data-elem=
ent_type=3D"widget" data-widget_type=3D"text-editor.default"><h3><b>Evaluat=
ing SRM as a response to climate change</b></h3><p>SRM could be very helpfu=
l or very harmful. It is the only known way to quickly stop or reverse the =
rise in global temperatures, and could be the only way to keep warming belo=
w 2=C2=B0C if mitigation proves insufficient.</p><p>But it could also have =
damaging side effects, could cause political tensions, and could distract p=
oliticians from cutting emissions. The stakes are high and nowhere are they=
 higher than in developing countries, which are&nbsp;<span style=3D"font-fa=
mily: var( --e-global-typography-text-font-family ), Open Sans; font-size: =
var( --e-global-typography-text-font-size );">on the front lines of climate=
 change. If SRM could work to reduce climate impacts, they stand to gain th=
e most. But if SRM goes wrong=E2=80=94or is rejected prematurely=E2=80=94th=
ey stand to lose the most.</span></p><p>Historically, most SRM research has=
 taken place in the Global North. A laissez-faire approach would mean the g=
ulf will continue to widen. It is therefore critical that the countries of =
the Global South play a more central role in the evaluation of SRM.</p><p>T=
he more Global South experts understand SRM and its implications, the bette=
r placed they will be to stand up for their interests, and&nbsp; to resist =
any bad-faith attempts to persuade them to support or oppose SRM.</p><h3><b=
>Is there a moral hazard in researching SRM?</b></h3><p>Some believe that t=
he very act of researching and discussing SRM could weaken a country=E2=80=
=99s commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions. This is sometimes calle=
d the moral hazard effect, or mitigation displacement.</p><p>The moral haza=
rd effect is a real concern, but to date there is little evidence that rese=
arching SRM weakens commitments to cutting emissions.&nbsp; Conversely, a n=
umber of studies have concluded that learning about SRM makes people feel m=
ore concerned about the risks of climate change.</p><p>&nbsp;</p></div></di=
v></div></div></section><section data-particle_enable=3D"false" data-partic=
